//   * Given an instance, calling code is expected to call the special
//     `destroy` method in order to free it after use, either by calling it explicitly
//     or by using a higher-level helper like the `use` method. Failing to do so risks
//     leaking the underlying Rust struct.
//
//   * We can't assume that calling code will do the right thing, and must be prepared
//     to handle Kotlin method calls executing concurrently with or even after a call to
//     `destroy`, and to handle multiple (possibly concurrent!) calls to `destroy`.
//
//   * We must never allow Rust code to operate on the underlying Rust struct after
//     the destructor has been called, and must never call the destructor more than once.
//     Doing so may trigger memory unsafety.
//
//   * To mitigate many of the risks of leaking memory and use-after-free unsafety, a `Cleaner`
//     is implemented to call the destructor when the Kotlin object becomes unreachable.
//     This is done in a background thread. This is not a panacea, and client code should be aware that
//      1. the thread may starve if some there are objects that have poorly performing
//     `drop` methods or do significant work in their `drop` methods.
//      2. the thread is shared across the whole library. This can be tuned by using `android_cleaner = true`,
//         or `android = true` in the [`kotlin` section of the `uniffi.toml` file](https://mozilla.github.io/uniffi-rs/kotlin/configuration.html).
//
// If we try to implement this with mutual exclusion on access to the pointer, there is the
// possibility of a race between a method call and a concurrent call to `destroy`:
//
//    * Thread A starts a method call, reads the value of the pointer, but is interrupted
//      before it can pass the pointer over the FFI to Rust.
//    * Thread B calls `destroy` and frees the underlying Rust struct.
//    * Thread A resumes, passing the already-read pointer value to Rust and triggering
//      a use-after-free.
//
// One possible solution would be to use a `ReadWriteLock`, with each method call taking
// a read lock (and thus allowed to run concurrently) and the special `destroy` method
// taking a write lock (and thus blocking on live method calls). However, we aim not to
// generate methods with any hidden blocking semantics, and a `destroy` method that might
// block if called incorrectly seems to meet that bar.
//
// So, we achieve our goals by giving each instance an associated `AtomicLong` counter to track
// the number of in-flight method calls, and an `AtomicBoolean` flag to indicate whether `destroy`
// has been called. These are updated according to the following rules:
//
//    * The initial value of the counter is 1, indicating a live object with no in-flight calls.
//      The initial value for the flag is false.
//
//    * At the start of each method call, we atomically check the counter.
//      If it is 0 then the underlying Rust struct has already been destroyed and the call is aborted.
//      If it is nonzero them we atomically increment it by 1 and proceed with the method call.
//
//    * At the end of each method call, we atomically decrement and check the counter.
//      If it has reached zero then we destroy the underlying Rust struct.
//
//    * When `destroy` is called, we atomically flip the flag from false to true.
//      If the flag was already true we silently fail.
//      Otherwise we atomically decrement and check the counter.
//      If it has reached zero then we destroy the underlying Rust struct.
//
// Astute readers may observe that this all sounds very similar to the way that Rust's `Arc<T>` works,
// and indeed it is, with the addition of a flag to guard against multiple calls to `destroy`.
//
// The overall effect is that the underlying Rust struct is destroyed only when `destroy` has been
// called *and* all in-flight method calls have completed, avoiding violating any of the expectations
// of the underlying Rust code.
//
// This makes a cleaner a better alternative to _not_ calling `destroy()` as
// and when the object is finished with, but the abstraction is not perfect: if the Rust object's `drop`
// method is slow, and/or there are many objects to cleanup, and it's on a low end Android device, then the cleaner
// thread may be starved, and the app will leak memory.
//
// In this case, `destroy`ing manually may be a better solution.
//
// The cleaner can live side by side with the manual calling of `destroy`. In the order of responsiveness, uniffi objects
// with Rust peers are reclaimed:
//
// 1. By calling the `destroy` method of the object, which calls `rustObject.free()`. If that doesn't happen:
// 2. When the object becomes unreachable, AND the Cleaner thread gets to call `rustObject.free()`. If the thread is starved then:
// 3. The memory is reclaimed when the process terminates.
//
// [1] https://stackoverflow.com/questions/24376768/can-java-finalize-an-object-when-it-is-still-in-scope/24380219
//


/**
 * FFI-safe wrapper around [`Node`] for Kotlin/Swift bindings.
 *
 * This wrapper provides identical functionality to [`Node`] with FFI-friendly
 * method signatures. All methods are synchronous and block on an internal Tokio
 * runtime. **Callers MUST invoke from a background thread** to avoid blocking
 * the main/UI thread.
 *
 * ## Message Receiving
 *
 * Unlike the Rust API where you get a raw channel receiver, the FFI wrapper
 * provides `poll_message()` and `wait_message()` methods for receiving `PubSub`
 * messages.
 *
 * ## Thread Safety
 *
 * The `poll_message()` and `wait_message()` methods are single-consumer: only
 * one task should call them at a time. Concurrent calls may see spurious
 * `ChannelClosed` errors.
 */
public interface FfiNodeInterface {
    
    /**
     * Manually add a peer to the routing table.
     *
     * This is useful for connecting to peers discovered out-of-band.
     * Note: The peer must have valid `PoW` to be accepted into routing table.
     */
    fun `addPeer`(`identityHex`: kotlin.String, `addresses`: List<kotlin.String>)
    
    /**
     * Bootstrap by connecting to a known peer.
     *
     * # Arguments
     * * `identity_hex` - Peer's identity (64 hex chars)
     * * `addresses` - At least one address (e.g., "192.168.1.10:4433")
     *
     * # Limits
     * - At least one address required
     * - Maximum 100 addresses
     */
    fun `bootstrap`(`identityHex`: kotlin.String, `addresses`: List<kotlin.String>)
    
    /**
     * Bootstrap using public seed nodes.
     */
    fun `bootstrapPublic`()
    
    /**
     * Retrieve a value from the DHT.
     */
    fun `dhtGet`(`keyHex`: kotlin.String): kotlin.ByteArray?
    
    /**
     * Store a value in the DHT (content-addressed).
     *
     * # Limits
     * - Maximum value size: 1 MiB
     */
    fun `dhtPut`(`value`: kotlin.ByteArray): kotlin.String
    
    /**
     * Store a value at a specific key in the DHT.
     *
     * # Limits
     * - Maximum value size: 1 MiB
     */
    fun `dhtPutAt`(`keyHex`: kotlin.String, `value`: kotlin.ByteArray)
    
    /**
     * Get all known peers from the routing table.
     *
     * Returns all peers discovered via bootstrap, RPC exchanges, or direct connections.
     */
    fun `getPeers`(): List<PeerContact>
    
    /**
     * Get this node's identity (64-character hex string).
     */
    fun `identityHex`(): kotlin.String
    
    /**
     * Check if a peer is being reached via relay.
     */
    fun `isPeerRelayed`(`identityHex`: kotlin.String): kotlin.Boolean
    
    /**
     * Get the local bind address (e.g., "0.0.0.0:4433").
     */
    fun `localAddress`(): kotlin.String
    
    /**
     * Open a raw bidirectional stream to a peer.
     *
     * Use this for voice/video telephony or other streaming applications where
     * you need direct access to a bidirectional byte stream without RPC framing.
     *
     * # Arguments
     * * `identity_hex` - Peer's identity (64 hex chars)
     *
     * # Returns
     * An `FfiBidirectionalStream` for reading/writing raw bytes.
     *
     * # Wire Format
     * Raw streams bypass RPC framing. Define your own wire protocol:
     * - Frame type prefix (audio=0x01, video=0x02)
     * - Timestamp for synchronization
     * - Sequence numbers for ordering
     *
     * # Errors
     * - `InvalidIdentity` if identity is not valid hex
     * - `NotFound` if peer not in routing table
     * - `ConnectionFailed` if connection establishment fails
     */
    fun `openStream`(`identityHex`: kotlin.String): FfiBidirectionalStream
    
    /**
     * Poll for next received message (non-blocking check, but sync FFI call).
     *
     * Returns `None` immediately if no message is available.
     * For efficient waiting, use `wait_message()` instead.
     *
     * **Note:** While the channel check is non-blocking, this is still a sync FFI
     * call that briefly enters the Tokio runtime. Call from a background thread.
     *
     * # Thread Safety
     * This method is single-consumer: only one task should call `poll_message` or
     * `wait_message` at a time. Concurrent calls may see spurious `ChannelClosed` errors.
     */
    fun `pollMessage`(): PubSubMessage?
    
    /**
     * Poll for an incoming RPC request (non-blocking).
     *
     * Returns `None` immediately if no request is available.
     * Use `respond_to_request()` to send a response.
     */
    fun `pollRequest`(): IncomingRequest?
    
    /**
     * Poll for an incoming raw stream (non-blocking).
     *
     * Returns `None` immediately if no stream is available.
     */
    fun `pollStream`(): FfiBidirectionalStream?
    
    /**
     * Probe if this node is publicly reachable using a helper peer.
     *
     * The helper peer will attempt to connect back to us and report success/failure.
     * Returns `true` if we're publicly reachable, `false` if behind NAT.
     */
    fun `probeReachability`(`helperIdentityHex`: kotlin.String): kotlin.Boolean
    
    /**
     * Publish a message to a `PubSub` topic.
     *
     * # Limits
     * - Topic must be non-empty and ≤256 bytes
     * - Data must be ≤64 KB
     */
    fun `publish`(`topic`: kotlin.String, `data`: kotlin.ByteArray)
    
    /**
     * Publish this node's addresses to the DHT.
     *
     * Use this to manually announce reachable addresses after network changes.
     * Typically called with addresses from `routable_addresses()`.
     */
    fun `publishAddress`(`addresses`: List<kotlin.String>)
    
    /**
     * Resolve an identity to contact information.
     */
    fun `resolve`(`identityHex`: kotlin.String): PeerContact?
    
    /**
     * Respond to an incoming RPC request.
     *
     * Must be called with the `request_id` from an `IncomingRequest` received via
     * `wait_request()` or `poll_request()`.
     *
     * Returns `true` if response was sent, `false` if `request_id` was invalid or expired.
     */
    fun `respondToRequest`(`requestId`: kotlin.ULong, `response`: kotlin.ByteArray): kotlin.Boolean
    
    /**
     * Get routable addresses for this node.
     */
    fun `routableAddresses`(): List<kotlin.String>
    
    /**
     * Send a request and wait for response.
     *
     * # Limits
     * - Maximum request size: 64 KB
     */
    fun `send`(`identityHex`: kotlin.String, `request`: kotlin.ByteArray): kotlin.ByteArray
    
    /**
     * Shutdown the node gracefully.
     */
    fun `shutdown`()
    
    /**
     * Subscribe to a `PubSub` topic.
     *
     * # Limits
     * - Topic must be non-empty and ≤256 bytes
     */
    fun `subscribe`(`topic`: kotlin.String)
    
    /**
     * Get list of subscribed topics.
     */
    fun `subscriptions`(): List<kotlin.String>
    
    /**
     * Get telemetry snapshot for monitoring.
     */
    fun `telemetry`(): Telemetry
    
    /**
     * Unsubscribe from a `PubSub` topic.
     */
    fun `unsubscribe`(`topic`: kotlin.String)
    
    /**
     * Wait for next received message with timeout.
     *
     * Blocks until a message is received or timeout expires.
     * Returns `None` on timeout.
     *
     * # Thread Safety
     * This method is single-consumer: only one task should call `poll_message` or
     * `wait_message` at a time. Concurrent calls may see spurious `ChannelClosed` errors.
     */
    fun `waitMessage`(`timeoutMs`: kotlin.ULong): PubSubMessage?
    
    /**
     * Wait for an incoming RPC request with timeout.
     *
     * Returns `None` if timeout expires without receiving a request.
     * Use `respond_to_request()` to send a response.
     *
     * **Call from a background thread** - this blocks until a request arrives or timeout.
     *
     * # Thread Safety
     * This method is single-consumer: only one task should call `wait_request` or
     * `poll_request` at a time.
     */
    fun `waitRequest`(`timeoutMs`: kotlin.ULong): IncomingRequest?
    
    /**
     * Wait for an incoming raw stream with timeout.
     *
     * Returns `None` if timeout expires without receiving a stream.
     * Use the returned `FfiBidirectionalStream` for reading/writing.
     *
     * **Call from a background thread** - this blocks until a stream arrives or timeout.
     *
     * # Thread Safety
     * This method is single-consumer: only one task should call `wait_stream` or
     * `poll_stream` at a time.
     *
     * # Usage for Voice/Video
     * ```kotlin
     * // Kotlin example
     * while (true) {
     * val stream = node.waitStream(5000) ?: continue
     * println("Incoming call from ${stream.peerIdentity()}")
     * // Read first byte to determine stream type
     * val typeBytes = stream.readExact(1)
     * when (typeBytes[0]) {
     * 0x01.toByte() -> handleAudioStream(stream)
     * 0x02.toByte() -> handleVideoStream(stream)
     * else -> stream.close()
     * }
     * }
     * ```
     */
    fun `waitStream`(`timeoutMs`: kotlin.ULong): FfiBidirectionalStream?
    
    companion object
}

